Call for Papers Workshop on Organizing Web Space ( WOWS ) In conjunction with ACM Digital Library '99 Radisson Hotel , Berkeley , CA , USA , August 14 th , 1999 Workshop Home Page : http : / / www . ccrl . neclab . com / dl 99 ws / Motivation - - - - - - - - - - Hypertext and hypermedia have emerged as primary means for structuring documentation and for accessing information . With the explosive growth of the WWW , most search retrieves a large number of documents . It has no aggregate structure which organizes distinct Web localities . Users have no global view of the entire Web from which to forage for relevant pages . As a solution to this problem , integration of content search and structure analysis has drawn the attention of many research communities , including CHI , IR , hypertext , hypermedia , digital libraries , and databases . It is believed that such integration can improve hypermedia document retrieval and management ; consequently increasing information utilization . The goals of this workshop is provide a forum for researchers and practitioners on the interactions among many research communities . In this workshop we focus the following areas : ( 1 ) organizing collection overviews and topic spaces ; ( 2 ) facilitating and assisting search and associating relevant results ; ( 3 ) visualizing structure of information within the WWW for navigation ; and ( 4 ) extension to a variety of media types . TOPICS OF INTEREST ( a non-exclusive list ) - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - Techniques for ( 1 ) organizing and visualizing collection overviews and topic spaces ; ( 2 ) organizing and visualizing the structure of information within the WWW ; ( 3 ) facilitating and assisting search and navigation ; ( 4 ) summarizing data and convert data into information ; ( 5 ) extensions to a variety of media types , such as scanned image documents , photographs , text , and video ; ( 6 ) classifying metadata ; ( 7 ) representing structure ( e . g . XML ) ; ( 8 ) considering user behavior ( e . g . access frequency and link navigation behavior ) ( 9 ) consideration authoring styles ( e . g . link structures ) ( 10 ) collaborative hypermedia environment ( e . g . Multivalent Document and social filtering ) Possible and promising applications areas to apply such techniques ( 1 ) XML content search , reorganization , and summarization ( 2 ) Web site content search , reorganization , and summarization ( 3 ) Organizing and visualizing query results as above ( 4 ) Video search , reorganization , and summarization ( 5 ) Such organizing and visualization may be customized / adapted based on various constraints / preference . Expected audience - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - These topics are of great interests of attendants for SIGIR and ACM DL as well of industrial participation from the related companies in the Bay area . The topics cover not only the area of hypertext / hypermedia and digital libraries but also the general scope of WWW . Short papers ( work-in-progress ) should be no more than 4 pages in length . Long papers should be no more than 3 , 000 words in length . Referees will consider originality , significance , technical soundness , and clarity of exposition . Electronic submissions are STRONGLY encouraged ! Please send abstract by May 25 , 1999 ( no more than 250 words in ASCII text ) of the paper via email including title of the paper , authors' names , and keywords . Postscript or pdf file of your paper should be sent by June 1 , 1999 . The title page must include the name and email address of the contact author as well as the type of papers ( i . e . short papers or long papers ) Email for Submission of Papers and Abstract : dl 99 @ hju . eu . tq
